The Stoic believes that nothing can be a good for man which does not pertain to himself; that he is therefore only concerned to know what his

nature is, and then to perfect it. All men indeed unconsciously make it their ultimate aim to bring themselves nearer to per-fection. But the wisc man, becoming conscious of this ultimate aim, leaves the indirect paths by which the artificial motives and social prejudices and passions of men seek for happiness, and shapes his course directly towards this goal.
